text: I think it probably goes back to that point I mentioned about complexity. It just is a bigger challenge in terms of being a manager in the space to actually get set up because of the difficulty in terms of getting the data and probably a little bit in terms of expertise. Because some of the things that I talked about before in terms of building models in systematic fixed income do require specialist skill sets. So you obviously need the quant skill set in terms of building backtest models, building risk models, et cetera. But you need fixed income relevant experience. You need to know how a balance sheet looks. You need to think about capital structure. You need to think about what drives the value of a firm and structural modeling, say, for example, in credit. And finally, you need to have people that understand analytics of CDS, of cash bonds, et cetera. So that sort of work that goes on in the background to kind of derive returns and exposures for all the bonds. So you need those kind of things in place to get table stakes, I guess, to be a systematic fixed. Income manager. I think it is ripe for being exploited, the space and ripe for being managed systematically. And there are definitely a growing number of entrants that we've seen, not just Bluecove, but plenty of others in the last few years. You can see clients looking for that offering a little bit more. I think, OK, it isn't a sufficient condition, but I think a necessary condition is that clients are willing to embrace managers beyond the traditional fixed income active offering. And indeed, you've seen a fast growth of passive investing. And I think that's a significant thing in fixed income. According to our figures, passive is growing probably about three times the rate that active is. So I think the preconditions are there of scientific active fixed income being attractive. We can also show you that it's traditional, that it's complementary to traditional investing in terms of low correlation. But those barriers to entry exist. And that's why I think it's been a somewhat slower process to build up. You kind of have to put enough energy into it to make sure that you can do all of those things I talked about and get to the end of it. It took us probably 18 months of R&D from founding the firm to have our first model. And therefore, the number of entrants that are willing to do that is going to be limited. But in our view, it should be the dominant way to manage fixed income. I think most folks, I'm sure you would agree, most folks listening would agree that systematic investing in general is the best way to invest. I don't see that fixed income is any different. Just because the complexities are there, that doesn't mean they can't be surmounted. And indeed, until fixed income active investing is ubiquitous, that complexity would probably mean that there are more inefficiencies. And then, as I was talking about before, in terms of the tactical environment, it's actually very promising. The systematic strategies thrive off volatility in general. The fact that spread dispersion is increasing and risk assets are faltering should probably mean an increased focus on fixed income. And then where should people come? Well, the strategies that can extract alpha in those periods and risk manage well. And again, systematic strategies are good at both of those. So, I mean, bottom line, we would expect to see a significant interest from clients and from new providers in this space. And we very much welcome that.
